byline.original: By GENE BYLINSKYDrawings by RALPH J. KELLNER

results.lead_paragraph: A FEW days after Lieut. Col. Aleksei Leonov's dramatic somersaults outside Voskhod II, James E. Webb, the voluble and vigorous space agency administrator, appeared before the Senate Aeronautical and Space Sciences Committee for what by now has became a ritual in the wake of spectacular Soviet space "firsts." He was asked what the National Aeronautics and Space Administration had to show for its $18 billion expended since 1959 to compare with the Soviet feat.
